                            GrammarTopicId = 2,
                            Description = "For actions happening at the moment of speaking",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n<p>The Present Continuous Tense is used to describe actions that are happening at the moment of speaking. It is formed using the verb 'to be' (am, is, are) followed by the -ing form of the main verb.</p>\r\n    <p>Structure:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Positive:</strong> Subject + am/is/are + verb(-ing)</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Negative:</strong> Subject + am/is/are + not + verb(-ing)</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Question:</strong> Am/Is/Are + subject + verb(-ing)?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Examples:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Positive:</strong> She <em>is watching</em> TV right now.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Negative:</strong> They <em>are not playing</em> football at the moment.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Question:</strong> Are you <em>reading</em> this lesson?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <h4>Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>This tense is specifically used for actions that are happening at the present moment. It highlights the temporary or ongoing nature of an action. Examples include:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I <em>am sitting</em> at my desk.</li>\r\n        <li>My friends <em>are eating</em> lunch.</li>\r\n        <li>The baby <em>is sleeping</em> right now.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Remember, actions described using the Present Continuous Tense are not permanent but rather temporary happenings.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 2,
