                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 4,
                            Description = "For planned actions or intentions",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>The future tense with 'going to' is used in English to talk about plans and intentions. It's a way to express what someone has decided to do in the future, often based on some current evidence or decision. This form is very common for speaking about future plans.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Structure</h4>\r\n    <p>The structure for forming sentences with 'going to' is:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><b>Positive:</b> Subject + be (am/is/are) + going to + base form of the verb</li>\r\n        <li><b>Negative:</b> Subject + be (am/is/are) + not + going to + base form of the verb</li>\r\n        <li><b>Question:</b> Be (Am/Is/Are) + subject + going to + base form of the verb?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Examples</h4>\r\n    <p>Here are some examples of 'going to' used for planned actions or intentions:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><b>Positive:</b> I <i>am going to</i> study English tonight.</li>\r\n        <li><b>Negative:</b> He <i>is not going to</i> go to the party tomorrow.</li>\r\n        <li><b>Question:</b> Are you <i>going to</i> visit your grandparents this weekend?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>We use 'going to' for:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Plans or intentions that are already decided before speaking.</li>\r\n        <li>When there is evidence or a clear indication that something will happen in the future. For example, \"Look at those dark clouds! It's going to rain.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Contraction with 'going to'</h4>\r\n    <p>In spoken English, 'going to' is often contracted to 'gonna', especially in informal situations. However, it's important to use the full form in written English or in more formal situations.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Remember!</h4>\r\n    <p>Choosing between 'going to' and 'will' for future actions depends on the situation. Use 'going to' for plans or intentions and 'will' for decisions made at the moment of speaking.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 4,
                            Text = "Future with 'going to'"
                        },
