                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 5,
                            Description = "To express ability or possibility",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>\r\n        The modal verbs <strong>\"can\"</strong> and <strong>\"could\"</strong> are used in English to express ability or possibility. At the A2 level, understanding how to use these verbs correctly is crucial for describing what someone is able to do or what might be possible.\r\n    </p>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h5>Using \"Can\" for Present Ability</h5>\r\n        <p>\r\n            <strong>\"Can\"</strong> is used to talk about someone's skill or general abilities in the present or future. Here's how you can structure a sentence with \"can\" to express ability:\r\n        </p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li><strong>Affirmative:</strong> Subject + can + base form of the verb. <br>Example: <em>I can swim.</em></li>\r\n            <li><strong>Negative:</strong> Subject + cannot/can't + base form of the verb. <br>Example: <em>She can't drive.</em></li>\r\n            <li><strong>Question:</strong> Can + subject + base form of the verb? <br>Example: <em>Can you speak English?</em></li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h5>Using \"Could\" for Past Ability</h5>\r\n        <p>\r\n            <strong>\"Could\"</strong> is the past tense of \"can\" and is used to talk about abilities someone had in the past but might not have anymore. Here is the basic structure:\r\n        </p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li><strong>Affirmative:</strong> Subject + could + base form of the verb. <br>Example: <em>I could read when I was four.</em></li>\r\n            <li><strong>Negative:</strong> Subject + could not/couldn't + base form of the verb. <br>Example: <em>He couldn't swim before his lessons.</em></li>\r\n            <li><strong>Question:</strong> Could + subject + base form of the verb? <br>Example: <em>Could she ride a bike when she was younger?</em></li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h5>\"Could\" for Possibility</h5>\r\n        <p>\r\n            We also use <strong>\"could\"</strong> to talk about possible actions or situations, especially when imagining scenarios:\r\n        </p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>Example: <em>We could go to the beach tomorrow if it's sunny.</em></li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    <p>\r\n        It's important to practice these structures to become comfortable expressing ability and possibility in English.\r\n    </p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 5,
                            Text = "Can/Could for Ability"
                        },
