                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 6,
                            Description = "To compare things and people",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n  <p>Comparatives and superlatives are used in English to compare things and people. They help us to express differences in quality, quantity, or degree among two or more subjects or objects.</p>\r\n  \r\n  <h4>Comparatives</h4>\r\n  <p>Comparatives are used to compare two things or people. To form comparatives, we generally add <strong>-er</strong> to the end of the adjective or adverb. For words that are longer, we use <strong>\"more\"</strong> before the adjective or adverb.</p>\r\n  <div>\r\n    <h5>Examples:</h5>\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>Small - <em>smaller</em></li>\r\n      <li>Happy - <em>happier</em></li>\r\n      <li>Beautiful - <em>more beautiful</em></li>\r\n      <li>Intelligently - <em>more intelligently</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <p>When using comparatives, we often use \"than\" to compare, as in \"<em>She is taller than her brother.</em>\"</p>\r\n  \r\n  <h4>Superlatives</h4>\r\n  <p>Superlatives are used to compare more than two things or people and to show who is the 'most' or 'least' of the group. To form superlatives, we generally add <strong>-est</strong> to the end of the adjective or adverb. For longer words, we use <strong>\"most\"</strong> or <strong>\"least\"</strong> before the adjective or adverb.</p>\r\n  <div>\r\n    <h5>Examples:</h5>\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>Small - <em>smallest</em></li>\r\n      <li>Happy - <em>happiest</em></li>\r\n      <li>Beautiful - <em>most beautiful</em></li>\r\n      <li>Intelligently - <em>most intelligently</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <p>Superlatives often need the article \"the\" because they point out a specific item or person, such as in \"<em>The tallest mountain is Mount Everest.</em>\"</p>\r\n  \r\n  <h4>Irregular Forms</h4>\r\n  <p>Some adjectives and adverbs have irregular comparative and superlative forms that do not follow the regular \"-er\" and \"-est\" or \"more\" and \"most\" forms.</p>\r\n  <div>\r\n    <h5>Examples:</h5>\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>Good - <em>better</em> - <em>best</em></li>\r\n      <li>Bad - <em>worse</em> - <em>worst</em></li>\r\n      <li>Far - <em>farther/further</em> - <em>farthest/furthest</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 6,
                            Text = "Comparatives and Superlatives"
                        },
