                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 7,
                            Description = "Such as 'in', 'at', 'on' for describing time",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>\r\n        Understanding prepositions of time is crucial for accurately describing when events take place. The prepositions 'in', 'at', and 'on' are commonly used to refer to different aspects of time. Each has its own set of rules for when it should be used.\r\n    </p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>1. \"In\" for Months, Years, Centuries, and Long Periods</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n        Use 'in' when talking about longer periods of time such as months, years, and centuries. It is also used for parts of the day. \r\n    </p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Months:</strong> in January, in February</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Years:</strong> in 1999, in 2020</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Centuries:</strong> in the 21st century</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Parts of the day:</strong> in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Note: Do not use 'in' with 'night'. Instead, use 'at night'.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>2. \"At\" for Clock Times, Holidays, Weekend</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n        'At' is used for specific times of the day, including clock times and specific times in expressions. It's also used for holidays and the word 'weekend'.\r\n    </p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Clock times:</strong> at 7 o'clock, at 12:30</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Specific times:</strong> at noon, at midnight, at night</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Holidays:</strong> at Christmas, at Easter</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Weekend:</strong> at the weekend (British English), but note that in American English, it's 'on the weekend'</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>3. \"On\" for Days and Dates</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n        Use 'on' when referring to specific days and dates. This includes days of the week, specific dates, and special days.\r\n    </p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Days of the week:</strong> on Monday, on Tuesday</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Dates:</strong> on the 5th of July, on December 25th</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Special days:</strong> on my birthday, on New Year’s Day</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Remembering these simple rules about 'in', 'at', and 'on' can greatly improve your ability to communicate time-related information in English. Practice using these prepositions in various sentences to master their usage.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 7,
                            Text = "Prepositions of Time"
                        },
                        new
                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 8,
                            Description = "Such as 'in', 'at', 'on' for describing location",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>Prepositions of place are essential for describing the location or position of objects, people, and places. The most common prepositions for indicating locations are <strong>'in'</strong>, <strong>'at'</strong>, and <strong>'on'</strong>. Understanding how to use these prepositions correctly is crucial for communicating locations accurately in English.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Using 'In'</h4>\r\n        <p>The preposition <strong>'in'</strong> is used to indicate that something is contained within a larger area or space. This can be used for countries, cities, rooms, or any enclosed space.</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>She lives <strong>in</strong> France.</li>\r\n            <li>I found it <strong>in</strong> the box.</li>\r\n            <li>We are <strong>in</strong> the park.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Using 'At'</h4>\r\n        <p>The preposition <strong>'at'</strong> is used to indicate a specific point or location. This can refer to addresses, specific locations, or places where events occur.</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>He is waiting <strong>at</strong> the bus stop.</li>\r\n            <li>Meet me <strong>at</strong> 123 Maple Street.</li>\r\n            <li>I'll see you <strong>at</strong> the entrance.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Using 'On'</h4>\r\n        <p>The preposition <strong>'on'</strong> is used to indicate a surface or a specific position on a line, street, or floor. This is often used for streets, surfaces, or when something is attached to or touching a vertical or horizontal surface.</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>The book is <strong>on</strong> the table.</li>\r\n            <li>She lives <strong>on</strong> Main Street.</li>\r\n            <li>There is a painting <strong>on</strong> the wall.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Tips for Remembering These Prepositions</h4>\r\n        <p>Remembering how to use 'in', 'at', and 'on' can be simplified with a few tips:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>Think of <strong>'in'</strong> for enclosed spaces.</li>\r\n            <li>Use <strong>'at'</strong> for specific points or locations.</li>\r\n            <li>Remember <strong>'on'</strong> for surfaces or being in contact with something.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n        <p>With practice, using these prepositions to describe locations will become more intuitive.</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 8,
                            Text = "Prepositions of Place"
                        },
