                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 9,
                            Description = "Such as 'must', 'should' for necessity and advice",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>Modal verbs are special verbs that are used to express necessity, possibility, permission, or ability. In this lesson, we will focus on modal verbs used to express necessity and advice, such as <strong>must</strong> and <strong>should</strong>.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h5>Must - Expressing Necessity</h5>\r\n    <p><strong>Must</strong> is a modal verb used to express something that is necessary or obligatory. It is used when the speaker believes something is important or mandatory. Here is the basic structure:</p>\r\n    <p><i>Subject + must + base form of the verb</i></p>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <p>Examples:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>You <strong>must</strong> wear a helmet while riding a bike.</li>\r\n            <li>We <strong>must</strong> submit the project by Friday.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n    <h5>Should - Giving Advice</h5>\r\n    <p><strong>Should</strong> is used to give advice, suggestions, or to say what is ideal or recommended. It is less strong than <strong>must</strong>, but it expresses an opinion or recommendation from the speaker.</p>\r\n    <p><i>Subject + should + base form of the verb</i></p>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <p>Examples:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>You <strong>should</strong> drink more water to stay hydrated.</li>\r\n            <li>They <strong>should</strong> consider taking a break to avoid burnout.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <h5>Notes on using must and should</h5>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Use <strong>must</strong> when you are certain that something is necessary.</li>\r\n        <li>Use <strong>should</strong> to make recommendations or give advice that is less forceful than an obligation.</li>\r\n        <li>The negative form of <strong>must</strong> is <strong>must not</strong> or <strong>mustn't</strong>, which indicates prohibition. For example: You <strong>must not</strong> smoke here.</li>\r\n        <li>The negative form of <strong>should</strong> is <strong>should not</strong> or <strong>shouldn't</strong>, used for advising against something. For example: You <strong>shouldn't</strong> stay up too late.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Understanding the use of these modal verbs can greatly improve your ability to express necessity and give advice in English, making your communication clear and effective.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 2,
                            Order = 9,
                            Text = "Simple Modal Verbs"
                        },
