                            GrammarTopicId = 22,
                            Description = "Affirmative, Negative, Questions",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Simple Present Tense - Affirmative, Negative, Questions</h4>\r\n    <p>The Simple Present tense is used to describe habits, unchanging situations, general truths, and fixed arrangements. It is a very basic but essential tense in English. Let's break it down into affirmative, negative, and question forms.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Affirmative Form</h4>\r\n    <p>To make an affirmative sentence in Simple Present, use the base form of the verb. Remember, for third person singular (he, she, it), you need to add an &apos;s&apos; or &apos;es&apos; to the verb.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I/We/You/They <strong>go</strong> to school every day.</li>\r\n        <li>He/She/It <strong>goes</strong> to school every day.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Negative Form</h4>\r\n    <p>To make a negative sentence in Simple Present, use <strong>do not</strong> (don't) for I/we/you/they and <strong>does not</strong> (doesn't) for he/she/it, followed by the base form of the verb.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I/We/You/They <strong>do not go</strong> to school on Sunday.</li>\r\n        <li>He/She/It <strong>does not go</strong> to school on Sunday.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Questions</h4>\r\n    <p>To form questions in Simple Present, invert the do/does and the subject, and use the base form of the verb.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Do</strong> I/we/you/they <strong>go</strong> to school every day?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Does</strong> he/she/it <strong>go</strong> to school every day?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Remember to use short answers for yes/no questions:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>- <strong>Do</strong> you like ice cream? - Yes, I <strong>do</strong>./No, I <strong>don't</strong>.</li>\r\n        <li>- <strong>Does</strong> she have a pen? - Yes, she <strong>does</strong>./No, she <strong>doesn't</strong>.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p><strong>Note:</strong> Be attentive to spelling changes for verbs that end in <strong>-s</strong>, <strong>-sh</strong>, <strong>-ch</strong>, <strong>-x</strong>, or <strong>-o</strong> when adding 's' or 'es' in the third person singular form (he, she, it). For example, he watches, she fixes, it goes.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 7,
                            Text = "Simple Present Tense"
                        },
