                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 29,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n  <h4>Can for Ability</h4>\r\n  <p>The modal verb <strong>can</strong> is used to express ability or the capacity to do something. It is a very common verb in English and is used in the present tense to talk about abilities that are true at the moment of speaking or in general.</p>\r\n  <h4>Structure</h4>\r\n  <p>The structure for <strong>can</strong> in sentences is simple:</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Positive: Subject + can + base form of the verb</li>\r\n    <li>Negative: Subject + cannot/can't + base form of the verb</li>\r\n    <li>Question: Can + subject + base form of the verb?</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h4>Examples</h4>\r\n  <div>\r\n    <p>Here are some examples to help illustrate this:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>I <strong>can</strong> swim.</li>\r\n      <li>She <strong>can</strong> speak three languages.</li>\r\n      <li>They <strong>cannot (can't)</strong> hear you.</li>\r\n      <li><strong>Can</strong> you drive a car?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <h4>Usage</h4>\r\n  <p>Using <strong>can</strong> for ability is useful in several contexts:</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>To talk about things that you know how to do.</li>\r\n    <li>To ask if someone knows how to do something or to request someone to do something if they are able.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Remember, when talking about past abilities, we typically use 'could', the past form of 'can'. However, for the A1 level, focusing on the present ability with 'can' is a great starting point.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 14,
                            Text = "Can for Ability"
                        },
