                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 30,
                            Description = "Affirmative, Negative, Questions",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Present Continuous Tense</h4>\r\n    <p>The Present Continuous Tense is used to talk about actions that are happening right now or around the current moment. It's also used for future plans or events and situations that are temporary.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Forming the Present Continuous Tense</h4>\r\n    <p>To form the Present Continuous Tense, use the formula:</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Subject + am/is/are + verb-ing</strong></p>\r\n    \r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Affirmative Sentences</h4>\r\n        <p>In affirmative sentences, we follow the structure mentioned above. Here are some examples:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>I <strong>am reading</strong> a book.</li>\r\n            <li>You <strong>are working</strong> on a project.</li>\r\n            <li>He <strong>is watching</strong> TV.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Negative Sentences</h4>\r\n        <p>To make negative sentences in the Present Continuous Tense, we simply add <strong>not</strong> after the auxiliary verb (am/is/are). For example:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>I <strong>am not sleeping</strong> right now.</li>\r\n            <li>She <strong>is not eating</strong> dinner.</li>\r\n            <li>They <strong>are not playing</strong> football.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n    <div>\r\n        <h4>Questions</h4>\r\n        <p>To ask questions in the Present Continuous Tense, invert the subject and the auxiliary verb. Here's the structure:</p>\r\n        <p><strong>Am/Is/Are + subject + verb-ing</strong>?</p>\r\n        <p>Some question examples include:</p>\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li><strong>Are you listening</strong> to me?</li>\r\n            <li><strong>Is he going</strong> to the park?</li>\r\n            <li><strong>Am I doing</strong> this right?</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n    <p>This tense is very useful for speaking about actions that are in progress at the moment of speaking or for plans that are already arranged in the near future. Remember, for actions happening right now, use the Present Continuous Tense.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 15,
                            Text = "Present Continuous Tense"
                        },
