                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 31,
                            Description = "who, what, where, when, why, how",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Question Words</h4>\r\n    <p>The English language uses specific words to ask questions. These words are known as <em>question words</em> or <em>wh-questions</em>. They help us gather information about someone, something, or a situation. Let's explore the most common question words: who, what, where, when, why, and how.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Who</strong> is used to ask about people. <em>Example:</em> Who is your best friend?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>What</strong> is used to ask about things, ideas, or activities. <em>Example:</em> What is your favorite book?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Where</strong> is used to ask about a place or location. <em>Example:</em> Where do you live?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>When</strong> is used to ask about time. <em>Example:</em> When is your birthday?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Why</strong> is used to ask about reasons or motivations. <em>Example:</em> Why do you study English?</li>\r\n        <li><strong>How</strong> is used to ask about the manner or way in which something is done. <em>Example:</em> How do you learn English?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>When forming questions with these words, remember to follow the basic structure:</p>\r\n    <div>\r\n        <p>Question Word + Auxiliary Verb + Subject + Main Verb + ...?</p>\r\n        <p><em>Example:</em> How do you make this cake?</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <p>However, note that not all questions follow this structure exactly, especially with <em>who</em>, <em>what</em>, and <em>which</em> when they act as the subject of the question. In these cases, the auxiliary verb may be omitted. For instance, <em>\"Who knows the answer?\"</em></p>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Using question words correctly will help you gather specific information and engage in more meaningful conversations in English. Practice them regularly in different contexts to become more comfortable with their usage.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 16,
                            Text = "Question Words"
                        },
                        new
                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 32,
                            Description = "always, usually, sometimes, never",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Basic Adverbs of Frequency: always, usually, sometimes, never</h4>\r\n    <p>Adverbs of frequency tell us how often something happens. The most common ones for beginners are <em>always</em>, <em>usually</em>, <em>sometimes</em>, and <em>never</em>. Here’s how you can use them:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>always</strong> – This means something happens 100% of the time. It's a sure thing. For example, \"She always goes to bed before 10 PM.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>usually</strong> – This indicates something happens most of the time, but not always, let’s say around 80-90% of the time. Example: \"He usually takes the bus to work.\" </li>\r\n        <li><strong>sometimes</strong> – This word tells us that something happens on some occasions, not very often and not very rarely, roughly 50% of the time. For example, \"They sometimes eat out at the restaurant.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>never</strong> – This means 0% of the time; it does not happen at all. For instance, \"I never drink coffee.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Placement of these adverbs is also important. They usually come before the main verb but after the verb 'to be'. For example:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\"She <strong>always</strong> <em>reads</em> before bed.\" (Before the main verb 'reads')</li>\r\n        <li>\"He <em>is</em> <strong>usually</strong> busy on Mondays.\" (After the verb 'to be' - 'is')</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>In questions and negatives, the placement rules stay the same:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Do you <strong>usually</strong> get up early?</li>\r\n        <li>She doesn’t <strong>always</strong> drink tea in the morning.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Understanding and using these adverbs correctly can help make your sentences more precise and convey your meaning more accurately about how often you do something.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 17,
                            Text = "Basic Adverbs of Frequency"
                        },
