                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 33,
                            Description = "and, but, or",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Basic Conjunctions: and, but, or</h4>\r\n    <p>Conjunctions are words that connect clauses or sentences. They also connect words in a list. The most basic conjunctions you need to know at the A1 level are <strong>and</strong>, <strong>but</strong>, and <strong>or</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>How to Use \"and\"</h4>\r\n    <p>The conjunction <strong>and</strong> is used to show addition. It combines ideas that are similar or related.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I like apples <strong>and</strong> bananas.</li>\r\n        <li>She studies English <strong>and</strong> works part-time.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>How to Use \"but\"</h4>\r\n    <p><strong>But</strong> is used to show contrast or the difference between two statements.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I like to swim <strong>but</strong> I don’t like to run.</li>\r\n        <li>He wanted to go to the concert <strong>but</strong> he didn't have enough money.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>How to Use \"or\"</h4>\r\n    <p><strong>Or</strong> is used to show choices or alternatives. It connects different possibilities.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Do you prefer tea <strong>or</strong> coffee?</li>\r\n        <li>We can go to the cinema <strong>or</strong> stay at home.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Tips on Using Basic Conjunctions</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>When making a list of more than two items, use <strong>and</strong> before the last item: \r\n            <em>She bought apples, bananas, and oranges.</em>\r\n        </li>\r\n        <li>You can use <strong>but</strong> to join sentences that could stand alone. For example:\r\n            <em>He is very funny, but he can be quite serious too.</em>\r\n        </li>\r\n        <li>Use <strong>or</strong> when you want to give someone a choice. It’s like saying, \"You can have this or that\":\r\n            <em>Would you like tea or coffee?</em>\r\n        </li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Understanding and using these basic conjunctions will help you to make your sentences more complex and interesting. They are fundamental to English grammar and are used frequently, both in writing and speaking.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 18,
                            Text = "Basic Conjunctions"
                        },
