                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 34,
                            Description = "this, that, these, those",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Demonstratives: this, that, these, those</h4>\r\n    <p>Demonstratives are words that we use to point to specific objects or people. In English, there are four main demonstratives: <em>this, that, these,</em> and <em>those</em>. They help us to specify whether the objects or people we are referring to are close to us or far away, and whether they are in singular or plural form.</p>\r\n    <p>Here's a simple breakdown of each one:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>This</strong> is used to refer to a singular object or person that is close to the speaker. For example: <em>\"This is my book.\"</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>That</strong> is used for a singular object or person that is away from the speaker. For instance: <em>\"That is a car.\"</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>These</strong> refers to multiple objects or people that are near the speaker. Like: <em>\"These are my friends.\"</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Those</strong> is for multiple objects or people that are not close to the speaker. Example: <em>\"Those are the mountains.\"</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p><strong>Usage Tips:</strong></p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Use <em>this</em> and <em>these</em> when the objects or people you're talking about are close to you either physically or in time (something that is happening now or happened recently).</li>\r\n        <li>Use <em>that</em> and <em>those</em> for objects or people that are further away in distance or time (something happening in the future, or that happened in the past).</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>To master the use of demonstratives, practice by identifying objects around you and narrating their presence using <em>this, that, these,</em> and <em>those</em>. Remember, choosing the correct demonstrative depends on the location (near or far) and the number (singular or plural) of the objects or people you are referring to.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 19,
                            Text = "Demonstratives"
                        },
                        new
                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 35,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Modal Verb 'Would like' for Polite Requests</h4>\r\n    <p>The modal verb <strong>'would like'</strong> is a polite way to make requests or express desires in English. It is a softer, more polite alternative to directly saying \"want\". This expression can be used in various situations, such as ordering food in a restaurant, making a wish, or asking for help in a courteous manner.</p>\r\n    <p>To use 'would like' in a sentence, follow this structure:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Subject + would like + [object/noun]</strong> for statements.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Would + subject + like + [object/noun]?</strong> for questions.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Examples:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>I would like a cup of coffee.</em> (Statement)</li>\r\n        <li><em>Would you like some help?</em> (Question)</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>When offering choices, you can follow 'would like' with 'to' and the base form of a verb:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Would you like to go to the movies tonight?</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>'Would like' can also be combined with 'prefer' to politely express a preference between options:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>I would like to have tea, please, but I would prefer coffee if possible.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Remember:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Using 'would like' makes your request sound more polite and less direct.</li>\r\n        <li>When speaking, the contraction 'I'd like' is frequently used and sounds even softer.</li>\r\n        <li>Adding 'please' at the end of the sentence will make your request even more polite.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 1,
                            Order = 20,
                            Text = "Modal Verb 'Would like' for Polite Requests"
                        },
