                            GrammarTopicId = 37,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Present Perfect Continuous Tense</h4>\r\n    <p>The Present Perfect Continuous tense is used to describe an action that began in the past and is still continuing in the present. This tense emphasizes the duration or ongoing nature of the action. It is formed using the auxiliary verbs \"have been\" or \"has been\" followed by the present participle (the \"-ing\" form of the main verb).</p>\r\n    <p>Structure:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Affirmative sentences: Subject + has/have + been + present participle (verb+ing)</li>\r\n        <li>Negative sentences: Subject + has/have + not + been + present participle (verb+ing)</li>\r\n        <li>Questions: Has/Have + subject + been + present participle (verb+ing)?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>For example:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>She <strong>has been waiting</strong> for the bus for 30 minutes.</li>\r\n        <li>They <strong>have been studying</strong> English for three years.</li>\r\n        <li>I <strong>haven't been feeling</strong> well lately.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Has</strong> he <strong>been working</strong> on that project long?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Key Uses:</p>\r\n    <ol>\r\n        <li>To describe an action that started in the past and continues to the present moment.</li>\r\n        <li>To express the duration of an action that is still happening.</li>\r\n        <li>With the words \"for\" and \"since\" to indicate the length of time the action has been happening.</li>\r\n        <li>Sometimes to describe an action that was recently happening or has just stopped, often with an effect in the present. For example, \"You look tired. Have you been working out?\"</li>\r\n    </ol>\r\n    <p>Remember, the Present Perfect Continuous is not used with actions that are complete or with stative verbs.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 3,
                            Order = 2,
                            Text = "Present Perfect Continuous Tense"
                        },
