                            GrammarTopicId = 39,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>What is Past Perfect Continuous Tense?</h4>\r\n    <p>The Past Perfect Continuous Tense is used to talk about an action or situation that started in the past and continued up to another point in the past. To form this tense, we use the structure: <strong>had been + present participle (verb+ing)</strong>. It emphasizes the duration or continuous nature of an action that was completed before another past action.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>When to Use Past Perfect Continuous</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>To describe an action that was ongoing for a period of time in the past and was completed by a certain time in the past.</li>\r\n        <li>To show cause and effect in the past where one action, happening over a period of time, affects another action.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Examples</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>She had been waiting for the bus for an hour when it finally arrived.</em></li>\r\n        <li><em>They had been traveling in Europe for a month before they ran out of money.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>How to Form the Past Perfect Continuous</h4>\r\n    <p>The structure of the Past Perfect Continuous tense is quite specific. Here is how you form it:</p>\r\n    <p>Subject + had been + verb (in its -ing form).</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Positive sentence example: <em>I had been working on that report for two weeks before it was due.</em></li>\r\n        <li>Negative sentence example: <em>He hadn't been feeling well for a while before he decided to see a doctor.</em></li>\r\n        <li>Question form example: <em>Had you been studying English long before you moved to the UK?</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Keywords Often Used with Past Perfect Continuous</h4>\r\n    <p>Some keywords or phrases can clue you in to when the Past Perfect Continuous might be used. These include: <strong>for, since, all morning/day/week, etc., before, when, by the time</strong>, and others that imply a continuous action or a period of time before a specific point in the past.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Comparison with Other Tenses</h4>\r\n    <p>It's important to distinguish Past Perfect Continuous from other tenses:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Unlike the Simple Past, which emphasizes completed actions, the Past Perfect Continuous stresses the duration or ongoing nature of past actions.</li>\r\n        <li>Compared to the Past Continuous, which is used to talk about ongoing actions at a specific point in the past, Past Perfect Continuous extends this action to reach a point further in the past.</li>\r\n        <li>The Past Perfect Simple tense focuses on completion of a past action before another, whereas Past Perfect Continuous highlights how long this action was happening before it stopped.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Understanding and using the Past Perfect Continuous can significantly enhance your storytelling and descriptions of past events, specifically by adding depth to the durations and reasons behind past actions.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 3,
                            Order = 4,
                            Text = "Past Perfect Continuous Tense"
