                            GrammarTopicId = 40,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Understanding the Future Continuous Tense</h4>\r\n    <p>The future continuous tense, also known as the future progressive tense, is used to express actions that will be ongoing at a specific point in the future. It is formed by combining the modal auxiliary verb \"will,\" the base form of the verb \"be,\" and the present participle (the \"-ing\" form) of the main verb.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Formula</h4>\r\n    <p>The structure for forming sentences in the future continuous tense is:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Positive sentences:</strong> Subject + will be + present participle (verb-ing)</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Negative sentences:</strong> Subject + will not be + present participle (verb-ing)</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Question form:</strong> Will + subject + be + present participle (verb-ing)?</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>This tense is commonly used in the following scenarios:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>To indicate an action that will be in progress at a specific time in the future. E.g., \"I will be studying at 8 PM tonight.\"</li>\r\n        <li>To describe an action that will occur in the normal course of events or as part of a plan. E.g., \"She will be attending the conference next month.\"</li>\r\n        <li>To ask politely about someone's plans without assuming anything. E.g., \"Will you be using the car tomorrow?\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n        \r\n    <h4>Examples</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Positive:</strong> \"They <em>will be waiting</em> for us when we arrive.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Negative:</strong> \"I <em>will not be going</em> to the party tomorrow.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Question:</strong> \"What <em>will you be doing</em> this weekend?\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Key Points to Remember</h4>\r\n    <p>The future continuous tense is not just about an action's future occurrence; it emphasizes the ongoing nature of an action at a future moment. It provides a dynamic way of expressing the future, making it invaluable for speaking and writing about future plans, actions in progress, or polite inquiries.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 3,
                            Order = 5,
                            Text = "Future Continuous Tense"
