                            GrammarTopicId = 42,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Future Perfect Continuous Tense</h4>\r\n    <p>The Future Perfect Continuous Tense is used to express an ongoing action that will be completed at some point in the future. It highlights the duration of the activity or how long it has been happening by the time a certain future moment arrives.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Formulation:</strong> This tense is formed using will have been + the present participle (the verb form ending in -ing).</p>\r\n    <p>For example:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>By 2025, they <em>will have been working</em> on this project for 10 years.</li>\r\n        <li>He <em>will have been studying</em> English for over two hours by the time we arrive.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <h4>When to Use:</h4>\r\n    <p>This tense is particularly useful for:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Emphasizing the duration of an action up to a certain point in the future.</li>\r\n        <li>Expressing a future action that is seen as continuous up to a certain moment.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <h4>Key Points:</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>The time expression is often included, e.g., \"for two weeks,\" \"since 1999,\" \"by 2023,\" to indicate the duration or the endpoint of the action.</li>\r\n        <li>Unlike the Future Perfect Tense, the continuous aspect focuses more on the process and duration rather than the completion.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>It's important to note that not all actions can be used with the Future Perfect Continuous Tense. Actions that do not clearly show progress or duration (non-continuous verbs) usually do not fit this tense.</p>\r\n</div>",
