                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Conditionals: First, Second, and Third</h4>\r\n    <p>Conditionals in English are sentences which express hypotheses or conditions and their possible outcomes. They can be categorized into three main types: First, Second, and Third conditionals. Each type deals with a different kind of situation.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>First Conditional</h4>\r\n    <p>The First Conditional is used for real or possible situations in the future. It often expresses situations where the condition is likely to be met:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Form:</strong> If + present simple, ... will + infinitive</li>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> If it rains tomorrow, we will stay at home.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Second Conditional</h4>\r\n    <p>The Second Conditional is used for unreal or hypothetical situations in the present or future. It expresses situations which are imaginary, unlikely, or hypothetical:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Form:</strong> If + past simple, ... would + infinitive</li>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> If I won the lottery, I would travel the world.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Third Conditional</h4>\r\n    <p>The Third Conditional is used for situations in the past that did not happen. It expresses the idea of something that could have happened in the past but did not:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Form:</strong> If + past perfect, ... would have + past participle</li>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> If I had known you were in town, I would have called you.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Each type of conditional has its specific uses and forms. Understanding the differences and uses of these conditionals can significantly improve your ability to express scenarios and their possible outcomes in English.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 3,
                            Order = 8,
                            Text = "Conditionals (First, Second, Third)"
                        },
