                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 56,
                            Description = "A comprehensive review of all tenses.",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Advanced Tenses Review</h4>\r\n    <p>The English language boasts a variety of tenses to express time and action. Each tense helps us understand when an action happens, whether it is in the past, present, or future. Let's dive into a comprehensive review of all tenses to understand their forms and uses.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Present Tenses</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Simple Present:</strong> Expresses habitual actions, general truths, and facts. Formed by using the base form of the verb (add \"s\" or \"es\" for he/she/it). <em>Example: She travels to Japan every year.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Present Continuous:</strong> Indicates actions happening at the moment of speaking or current but temporary situations. Formed with am/is/are + verb-ing. <em>Example: They are watching a movie now.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Present Perfect:</strong> Describes actions that occurred at an unspecified time in the past or actions that started in the past and continue up to the present. Formed with has/have + past participle. <em>Example: I have finished my homework.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Present Perfect Continuous:</strong> Used for actions that began in the past and continue up to the present, especially with an emphasis on duration. Formed with has/have + been + verb-ing. <em>Example: She has been studying English for five years.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Past Tenses</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Simple Past:</strong> Used for actions completely finished at a specific time in the past. The form is the verb's past form. <em>Example: He visited Paris last summer.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Past Continuous:</strong> Indicates actions happening at a specific moment in the past or to express a longer action interrupted by a shorter action in the past. Formed with was/were + verb-ing. <em>Example: We were having dinner when the phone rang.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Past Perfect:</strong> Describes actions that were completed before another action or time in the past. Formed with had + past participle. <em>Example: She had left before you arrived.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Past Perfect Continuous:</strong> Used for actions that were ongoing in the past up until another moment or action in the past. Formed with had been + verb-ing. <em>Example: They had been playing tennis for two hours before it started raining.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Future Tenses</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Simple Future:</strong> Indicates actions that will happen in the future. Formed with will/shall + base verb. <em>Example: I will travel to France next year.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Future Continuous:</strong> Used to describe what will be happening at a particular moment in the future. Formed with will be + verb-ing. <em>Example: This time next week, I will be lying on the beach.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Future Perfect:</strong> Describes actions that will have been completed before some other action or time in the future. Formed with will have + past participle. <em>Example: By 2023, they will have finished the project.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Future Perfect Continuous:</strong> Used to show how long an action will have continued by a certain time in the future. Formed with will have been + verb-ing. <em>Example: By next month, I will have been living in Paris for a year.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Understanding and mastering the uses of these tenses allows for more accurate and expressive communication in English. Each tense provides a unique way to convey the time and nature of actions, enabling speakers to share detailed and precise information about their experiences, plans, and the world around them.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 1,
                            Text = "Advanced Tenses Review"
                        },
