                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 58,
                            Description = "Advanced",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Understanding Advanced Passive Voice</h4>\r\n    <p>The passive voice in English is used to shift the focus from the doer (subject) of the action to the receiver (object) of the action. At an advanced level, understanding the nuances and various forms can greatly enhance your writing and speaking abilities.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Forms and Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>The passive voice can be constructed in various tenses, and its usage depends on the focus of the sentence. Here are some advanced structures:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Present Perfect Passive:</strong> \"The work has been completed.\" This form is used to talk about actions that have an impact on the present.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Modal Verbs in Passive:</strong> Modal verbs can be used with passive voice, for instance, \"The book must be returned by Tuesday.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Passive Infinitive:</strong> Often used after modal verbs or in formal writings to express necessity or possibility, e.g., \"The document is to be submitted by Friday.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Passive Gerund:</strong> Using passive voice in gerund form can help in making general statements, such as in \"Being pushed too hard can lead to stress.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Types of Passive Constructions</h4>\r\n    <p>Besides the straight conversion of active to passive voice, there are advanced constructions to consider:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Reporting Verbs:</strong> When reporting speech or thoughts in a more formal or academic way, passive voice is often used. For example, \"It is said that the company is planning to expand.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Passive Voice with 'Get':</strong> Informal situations often use 'get' instead of 'be' for the passive voice. For example, \"He got promoted last month.\"</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Using 'By' Phrase:</strong> While the agent (doer of the action) is often omitted in passive sentences for focus or because it's unknown, it can be included using a 'by' phrase. E.g., \"The cake was eaten by the children.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Nuances and Considerations</h4>\r\n    <p>Understanding when and why to use the passive voice instead of the active voice has to do with the speaker or writer's intent and the focus they wish to convey. In academic writing, the passive voice is often preferred to focus on the action or result rather than the actor. However, excessive use can lead to unclear or cumbersome sentences, so it's essential to maintain a balance between active and passive constructions for clarity and dynamism in your language.</p>\r\n\r\n    <p>Moreover, in storytelling or descriptive writing, passive voice can create an intriguing mystique around the subject of action, making it a strategic choice in certain narratives.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 3,
                            Text = "Passive Voice"
                        },
