                            GrammarTopicId = 60,
                            Description = "Advanced",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Advanced Points in Reported Speech</h4>\r\n    <p>When delving into reported speech at an advanced B2 level, certain nuances and rules become significantly important. Understanding these complex aspects will enhance your ability to convey messages indirectly and accurately in English.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Backshifting</h4>\r\n    <p>One fundamental aspect of reported speech is the practice of backshifting. This involves changing the tense of the original speech when it's reported. However, it's crucial to recognize situations where backshifting isn't necessary. This usually occurs when the reported statement is about a universal truth, a habit, or when the original statement is still applicable in the present context.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Changes in Modal Verbs</h4>\r\n    <p>Modal verbs undergo changes in reported speech to reflect distance in time or reality. For instance:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\"Can\" changes to \"could\".</li>\r\n        <li>\"Will\" changes to \"would\".</li>\r\n        <li>\"May\" often changes to \"might\".</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>Note that \"must\" can remain the same or change to \"had to\" depending on the context and the speaker's intent.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Reporting Questions</h4>\r\n    <p>When reporting questions, it's essential to pay attention to the structure:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Yes/No questions should be transformed using \"if\" or \"whether\".</li>\r\n        <li>WH-questions retain the WH-word (what, where, when, etc.) but the sentence structure changes to that of a statement.</li>\r\n        <li>The tense, pronouns, and place/time expressions need to be adjusted according to the rules of backshifting and context.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Reporting Commands and Requests</h4>\r\n    <p>Commands and requests in reported speech are often introduced by verbs such as \"ask\", \"tell\", or \"order\", and the verb in the original command is changed to the infinitive form:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>E.g., \"Close the door,\" he said. → He asked me to close the door.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Changes in Time and Place Expressions</h4>\r\n    <p>Expressions of time and place need to be adjusted to fit the context of the report:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\"Here\" changes to \"there\".</li>\r\n        <li>\"Now\" changes to \"then\".</li>\r\n        <li>\"Today\" changes to \"that day\", and so on.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Mixed Reported Speech</h4>\r\n    <p>In advanced reporting, sometimes you need to mix tenses in the reported speech. This happens when the statement combines something true at the time with something that is still true when reported. It's essential to carefully consider the context and meaning to decide when to backshift and when not to.</p>\r\n\r\n    <p>Mastering these advanced aspects of reported speech expands your ability to communicate complex thoughts and nuances in English. Practice with varied and complex sentences to fully grasp each nuance.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 5,
                            Text = "Reported Speech"
                        },
