                            GrammarTopicId = 61,
                            Description = "Advanced",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Relative Clauses - Advanced</h4>\r\n    <p>Relative clauses are used to give additional information about a noun in a sentence. These clauses are introduced by relative pronouns like <em>who, whom, whose, which,</em> and <em>that</em> or relative adverbs like <em>where, when,</em> and <em>why</em>. In this advanced overview, we will explore reduced relative clauses, the choice between <em>who</em> and <em>whom</em>, and the use of <em>whose</em>, along with punctuation rules for defining and non-defining relative clauses.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Reduced Relative Clauses</h4>\r\n    <p>Reduced relative clauses allow us to shorten a sentence by removing the relative pronoun and the verb to be. They are mainly used in defining relative clauses. For example, the sentence \"The book that is on the table is mine\" can be reduced to \"The book on the table is mine\".</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Who vs. Whom</h4>\r\n    <p>The relative pronoun <em>who</em> is used for the subject of the clause, and <em>whom</em> is used for the object of the clause or after a preposition. In everyday English, <em>who</em> is often used instead of <em>whom</em>, but <em>whom</em> is still preferred in formal writing. For example, \"The person whom I saw was tall\" can be more informally written as \"The person who I saw was tall\".</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Use of Whose</h4>\r\n    <p>The relative pronoun <em>whose</em> is used to show possession. It can refer to both people and things. For example, \"The woman whose car broke down was late for the meeting\" gives information about the woman by describing something she possesses (her car).</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Punctuation for Defining and Non-defining Relative Clauses</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Defining relative clauses</strong> provide essential information about the noun they modify. They do not require commas. For instance, \"The house that Jack built is big\" specifies which house by using a defining relative clause.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Non-defining relative clauses</strong> add extra information that could be left out without changing the meaning of the sentence. They are separated from the rest of the sentence by commas. For example, \"Jack's house, which he built himself, is big\" offers additional information about Jack's house and is set off by commas.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>In summary, advanced use of relative clauses involves understanding when and how to reduce clauses, choose the appropriate relative pronoun or adverb, and apply correct punctuation depending on whether the clause is defining or non-defining. With practice, these structures can add precision and variety to your writing and speaking.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 6,
                            Text = "Relative Clauses"
                        },
