                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 67,
                            Description = "Advanced",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Advanced Phrasal Verbs</h4>\r\n    <p>Phrasal verbs are an integral part of the English language, especially at an advanced level. They consist of a verb and one or more prepositions or adverbs; the combination creates a meaning different from the original verb. Understanding these can significantly improve your fluency and comprehension of English.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <p>To master advanced phrasal verbs, it's crucial to not only memorize their meanings but also to understand their usage in context. Here are some tips:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Learn them in context:</strong> Rather than memorizing lists, learn phrasal verbs as you encounter them in conversations, books, or films. This helps in understanding their practical usage.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Use a phrasal verb diary:</strong> Keep a record of new phrasal verbs you learn, along with example sentences. Regularly review and try to use them in your own sentences.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Understand the nuances:</strong> Many phrasal verbs have subtle differences in meaning based on the preposition or adverb used. Pay attention to these nuances.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Practice regularly:</strong> Use these verbs in your spoken and written English as often as possible. The more you use them, the more naturally they will come to you.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Here are some examples of advanced phrasal verbs:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Come across:</strong> to find something or someone by chance. <em>I came across an old friend in the library.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Put forward:</strong> to propose or suggest something. <em>She put forward a new plan at the meeting.</em></li>\r\n        <li><strong>Break down:</strong> to start to cry. <em>He broke down when he heard the bad news.</em> This is a clear example of how context is vital, as \"break down\" can also mean other things like a vehicle ceasing to function.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Get over:</strong> to recover from an illness or an emotional setback. <em>It took her months to get over the flu.</em></li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Remember, the key to mastering advanced phrasal verbs lies in consistent practice, use in context, and continuous exposure to English through various mediums. This way, you'll not only learn their meanings but also the most appropriate contexts to use them.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 12,
                            Text = "Phrasal Verbs"
                        },
