                            GrammarTopicId = 70,
                            Description = "Advanced. Expressing wishes and regrets in complex sentences",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Wish/If only - Expressing Wishes and Regrets</h4>\r\n    <p>Using <em>wish</em> and <em>if only</em> in English allows speakers to express wishes, desires, or regrets about the present and past, and even hypotheses about the future in a more advanced and complex manner. These structures can add depth to language use, conveying emotions such as longing, dissatisfaction, or hypothetical thinking.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Wish + Past Simple</h4>\r\n    <p>When we want to express a wish about the present or complain about a current situation, we use <em>wish</em> followed by a verb in the past simple. Even though we use a past tense verb, we are talking about the present.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> \"I <em>wish I knew</em> the answer.\" (The speaker does not know the answer now, but wishes they did.)</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>If only + Past Simple</h4>\r\n    <p><em>If only</em> is used similarly to <em>wish</em>, but it can add a stronger sense of regret or a stronger wish. It is also followed by a verb in the past simple when talking about the present.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> \"If only I <em>had</em> more time.\" (The speaker is currently lacking time and strongly wishes for more.)</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Wish/If only + Past Perfect</h4>\r\n    <p>When expressing regret about past actions or situations that cannot be changed, use <em>wish</em> or <em>if only</em> followed by the past perfect.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> \"I <em>wish I had studied</em> harder for the exam.\" (The speaker regrets not studying harder in the past.)</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Wish + would + infinitive</h4>\r\n    <p>When hoping for a change in a situation or someone’s behavior, not influenced by the speaker, use <em>wish</em> followed by <em>would</em> and the base form of the verb.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Example:</strong> \"I wish you <em>would stop</em> smoking.\" (The speaker desires someone else to change their behavior.)</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Wish/If only for Future Hypotheticals</h4>\r\n    <p>Though less common, <em>wish</em> and <em>if only</em> can be used to talk about hypothetical situations in the future, often using conditional structures.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\"I wish I could see you tomorrow.\" (Expressing a desire for a future situation that might not be possible.)</li>\r\n        <li>\"If only we could live in a world without pollution.\" (A strong wish for a future hypothetical situation.)</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Remember, using <em>wish</em> and <em>if only</em> appropriately requires understanding the nuance of tense usage and the subtleties of expressing desires or regrets. Being able to construct and understand these sentences adds a rich layer of expression to your English communication skills.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 4,
                            Order = 15,
                            Text = "Wish/If only"
                        },
