                        {
                            GrammarTopicId = 78,
                            Description = "Complex forms of passive voice",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Advanced Passive Structures in English</h4>\r\n    <p>The passive voice in English is a pivotal element in effective writing and speaking, providing a way to emphasize the action itself or the recipient of the action rather than who or what is performing the action. At an advanced level, understanding complex forms of passive voice broadens the ability to articulate thoughts precisely and diversely. These advanced structures include passive modals, passive causatives, and passives with reporting verbs.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Passive Modals</h4>\r\n    <p>When using modal verbs (can, could, should, etc.) in the passive voice, the structure typically follows this pattern: modal verb + be + past participle. For example:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>The work can be done by tomorrow.</li>\r\n        <li>The book should be read by all students.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Passive Causatives</h4>\r\n    <p>This structure is often used to indicate that someone has arranged for something to be done by another person. In English, this is commonly formed with 'get' or 'have' followed by the object and a past participle. For instance:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>I had my car serviced last week. (Equivalent to \"I arranged for someone to service my car.\")</li>\r\n        <li>She got her hair cut yesterday. (Meaning \"She arranged for someone to cut her hair.\")</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Passives with Reporting Verbs</h4>\r\n    <p>Sometimes, passive structures are employed with reporting verbs such as say, believe, report, and think to convey information or rumors in a more indirect and perhaps formal or academic manner. This is particularly useful when the focus is on the information or belief rather than on who holds that belief. Examples include:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>It is said that he is the best in the field.</li>\r\n        <li>The product is thought to be harmful to the environment.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Each of these advanced passive structures provides a nuanced way to present information, emphasizing different elements of the sentence as needed. Mastery of these forms can significantly enhance one's ability to write and speak in English effectively, particularly in academic, formal, or professional settings.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
                            Order = 3,
                            Text = "Advanced Passive Structures"
                        },
