                            GrammarTopicId = 81,
                            Description = "Complex relative clauses for adding detailed information.",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Complex Relative Clauses for Adding Detailed Information</h4>\r\n    <p>At an advanced (C1) level, understanding and using complex relative clauses correctly plays a crucial role in enhancing the precision, fluency, and sophistication of your English. These clauses not only provide detailed information about a noun but also allow you to incorporate additional ideas without the need for multiple sentences.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Complex relative clauses often involve:\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>Using <strong>whom</strong> or <strong>whose</strong> for people, and <strong>which</strong> for things.</li>\r\n            <li>Integrating prepositions within the clause, usually preceding the relative pronoun (e.g., <em>The article, in which the author elaborates on her theory, has sparked a lot of debate</em>).</li>\r\n            <li>Employing reduced relative clauses, where the relative pronoun and the verb (often 'be') are omitted (e.g., <em>The students attending the seminar must register online</em>).</li>\r\n            <li>Using non-defining relative clauses, which are not essential to the meaning of the sentence and are set off by commas (e.g., <em>London, which is known for its historical landmarks, is a popular tourist destination</em>).</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </p>\r\n\r\n    <p>It's also important to recognize that in complex relative clauses, the choice of pronoun can impact the clarity and formality of your expression. <em>Whom</em>, for example, is more formal and often used in writing or formal speech, while <em>who</em> is more common in everyday conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n    <p>Furthermore, understanding how to properly use <em>whose</em> can add a layer of complexity and detail, as it shows possession. For example, <em>The novelist, whose books have sold millions of copies, was awarded a literary prize</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n    <p>Another advanced feature of complex relative clauses is the ability to nest them within each other, providing layers of information. However, this should be done with care to maintain clarity and avoid confusion for the reader or listener.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Practice and Application</h4>\r\n    <p>Mastering complex relative clauses involves regular practice and exposure to varied English texts, both written and spoken. Reading academic works, formal documents, and literature can expose you to numerous examples of these clauses in use. Equally, writing exercises that focus on integrating complex relative clauses into your own work can greatly improve your fluency and the sophistication of your language.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
                            Order = 6,
                            Text = "Relative Clauses"
                        },
