                            GrammarTopicId = 85,
                            Description = "Reporting complex statements, questions, and commands.",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Understanding Reported Speech at a C1 Level</h4>\r\n    <p>Reported speech is a method used to convey what someone else has said without quoting them directly. At a C1 level, it's important to grasp subtleties and variations, especially when dealing with complex statements, questions, and commands.</p>\r\n    <p>When reporting <strong>complex statements</strong>, the tense typically shifts back one step compared to the original statement. For example, present simple turns into past simple, and present perfect turns into past perfect. However, this shift isn't necessary if the statement is still relevant or if it refers to a universal truth.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Reporting questions</strong> requires a change in structure: the sentence order moves from the question format to a statement format. Thus, \"Do you like coffee?\" when reported becomes \"He asked if I liked coffee.\" Notice the omission of the auxiliary verb for yes/no questions and the retention of question word order for 'wh' questions, without actually framing it as a direct question.</p>\r\n    <p>When it comes to <strong>commands and requests</strong>, the verb usually changes to the infinitive form, and modal verbs like \"can\" or \"could\" are often introduced. For instance, \"Close the door, please\" can be reported as \"She asked me to close the door.\"</p>\r\n    <h4>Key Points for Mastery</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Understand the nuanced changes in verb tense and structure, especially in the context of keeping reported speech relevant to the listener.</li>\r\n        <li>Be familiar with reporting verbs that might change the nuance of the reported speech, such as 'claim', 'advise', 'insist', and how they might alter the perception of certainty or advice in the statement.</li>\r\n        <li>Recognize the importance of punctuation and sentence restructuring when moving from direct to reported speech, primarily to maintain clarity and accuracy.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>In conclusion, mastering reported speech at a C1 level involves more than understanding basic rules. It includes a deep grasp of context, verb tense nuances, and the ability to maintain the original meaning without using the exact words spoken. As such, practice with various forms of speech and reporting structures becomes invaluable for anyone looking to achieve proficiency at this level.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
                            Order = 10,
                            Text = "Reported Speech"
                        },
