                            GrammarTopicId = 91,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Understanding Parallel Structures</h4>\r\n    <p>Parallel structure, also known as parallelism, refers to the use of similar patterns of words to show that two or more ideas have the same level of importance. This can happen at the word, phrase, or clause level. The usual way to join parallel structures is with the use of coordinating conjunctions such as \"and\" or \"or.\"</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Examples and Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>Here are some examples to illustrate parallel structures:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Incorrect: She likes cooking, jogging, and to read.</li>\r\n        <li>Correct: She likes cooking, jogging, and reading.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>In the correct example, all three elements in the series are gerunds, forming a parallel triad.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Incorrect: He wanted to learn more about careers in teaching, in the medical field, and business.</li>\r\n        <li>Correct: He wanted to learn more about careers in teaching, in the medical field, and in business.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <p>The corrected sentence now clearly parallels \"in teaching,\" \"in the medical field,\" and \"in business.\"</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Why Use Parallel Structures?</h4>\r\n    <p>Parallel structures are not only a matter of correctness but also of clarity and elegance. They make sentences easier to understand by providing a clear, concise pattern. They can also add a rhythmic and forceful effect to your writing, making your sentences more effective and engaging to the reader.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Tips for Maintaining Parallelism</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>When creating a list or series, make sure each item is parallel by keeping them in the same form.</li>\r\n        <li>In comparisons or contrasts, match nouns with nouns, gerunds with gerunds, clauses with clauses, and so on.</li>\r\n        <li>Parallel construction extends to coordinating conjunctions; ensure that the structure before and after conjunctions like \"and,\" \"but,\" or \"or\" are parallel.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Advanced Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>At the C1 level, you're encouraged to play with structures, breaking parallelism deliberately for effect in creative writing or to highlight a particular point. However, ensure that the deviation serves a purpose and doesn't inadvertently confuse your reader.</p>\r\n\r\n    <p>In conclusion, mastering parallel structures can significantly refine your writing style, improve readability, and convey your ideas more effectively. It’s a powerful tool that, when used properly, can enhance the overall quality of your writing.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
                            Order = 16,
                            Text = "Parallel Structures"
                        },
