                            GrammarTopicId = 93,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Understanding Relative Pronouns and Adverbs</h4>\r\n    <p>Relative pronouns and adverbs are used to introduce relative clauses, which are clauses that provide additional information about a noun without beginning a new sentence. This mechanism is fundamental for achieving fluidity and specificity in English communication, especially at an advanced level such as C1.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Relative Pronouns</h4>\r\n    <p>The most common relative pronouns are <strong>who, whom, whose, which,</strong> and <strong>that</strong>. They serve different purposes:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Who</strong> and <strong>whom</strong> refer to people, with \"who\" as the subject and \"whom\" as the object of the relative clause.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Whose</strong> indicates possession.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Which</strong> refers to animals and things.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>That</strong> can refer to people, animals, and things, often used in defining (restrictive) clauses.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Relative Adverbs</h4>\r\n    <p>Relative adverbs include <strong>where, when,</strong> and <strong>why</strong>. They introduce relative clauses by referring to a place, time, or reason:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><strong>Where</strong> introduces clauses referring to a place.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>When</strong> introduces clauses referring to a time.</li>\r\n        <li><strong>Why</strong> introduces clauses referring to a reason, and is often used with the word \"reason.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Usage Examples</h4>\r\n    <p>Here are some practical examples to highlight their usage:</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>The professor <strong>who</strong> teaches English is retiring. (Who refers to the professor; thus, it's the subject of the clause)</li>\r\n        <li>The book <strong>that</strong> I borrowed was fascinating. (That refers to the book; it is used in a defining clause)</li>\r\n        <li>The house <strong>where</strong> I grew up was demolished. (Where refers to the place)</li>\r\n        <li>I remember the day <strong>when</strong> we first met. (When refers to the time)</li>\r\n        <li>The reason <strong>why</strong> he left is still a mystery. (Why refers to the reason)</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Advanced Considerations</h4>\r\n    <p>At a C1 level, it's also crucial to know when the omission of a relative pronoun is possible. This is often the case in defining relative clauses where the pronoun is the object. For example, \"The book you borrowed is overdue.\" Here, \"that\" is omitted.</p>\r\n    <p>Additionally, understanding the nuances of choosing between \"who\" and \"whom,\" and the correct use of \"whose\" in formal and informal contexts will enhance your linguistic precision and stylistic versatility. The flexibility and complexity of relative pronouns and adverbs allow for expressive and nuanced English, marking the proficiency of an advanced speaker.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
