                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Degrees of Certainty</h4>\r\n    <p>Understanding and expressing different <b>degrees of certainty</b> is a vital skill in English, especially at an advanced level like C1. This concept reflects how sure we are about the information or action we are referring to.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Present and Future Certainty</h4>\r\n    <p>For expressing certainty in the present or future, modals like <i>will</i>, <i>can</i>, and <i>may</i> are commonly used.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><b>Will</b> - absolute certainty about future events: \"The train will arrive at 6 PM.\"</li>\r\n        <li><b>Can</b> - high degree of certainty (but not absolute) about present situations: \"She can be very persuasive when she wants to be.\"</li>\r\n        <li><b>May</b>/<b>Might</b> - less certain, indicates a possibility: \"I may go to the party tonight.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Past Certainty</h4>\r\n    <p>To express certainty about the past, the modals <i>must</i>, <i>could</i>, and <i>might</i> are often used with a perfect aspect.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><i>Must have + past participle</i> - Conveys a high degree of certainty about a past action: \"He must have left the house early, his car is not here.\"</li>\r\n        <li><i>Could have + past participle</i> - Suggests a possibility that something happened in the past: \"She could have taken the earlier train.\"</li>\r\n        <li><i>Might have + past participle</i> - Indicates an even lesser degree of certainty than \"could have\": \"They might have missed the bus.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Negative Forms</h4>\r\n    <p>Negative forms imply the speaker's belief that something is unlikely or didn't happen.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><i>Can’t/couldn't + base form</i> for present or past belief respectively: \"He can't be serious.\" / \"He couldn't have known about the surprise.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Adverbs to Express Certainty</h4>\r\n    <p>Adverbs such as <i>definitely</i>, <i>probably</i>, <i>possibly</i>, and <i>certainly</i> can modify verbs or the entire sentence to express degrees of certainty without relying solely on modals.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\"She will definitely go to the meeting.\" - High certainty.</li>\r\n        <li>\"They are probably at home.\" - Medium certainty.</li>\r\n        <li>\"You could possibly win the game.\" - Low certainty.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Mastering the variations in expressing degrees of certainty allows for nuanced and precise communication, particularly important in professional and academic contexts.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 5,
                            Order = 19,
                            Text = "Degrees of Certainty"
                        },
