                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <h4>Advanced Passive Constructions in English</h4>\r\n    <p>Understanding Advanced Passive Constructions broadens the ways we can express ideas, particularly focusing on the action rather than who or what performs the action. This advanced level topic moves beyond the basic passive forms (\"be\" verb + past participle) to include a variety of structures that offer nuance and precision in academic, formal, or written English.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>1. Using 'Get' Instead of 'Be'</h4>\r\n    <p>While not formal, using \"get\" in place of \"be\" is common in conversational English to form passive constructions. This form emphasizes the action or change of state rather than the formality of the situation.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"She got promoted last year,\" instead of \"She was promoted last year.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>2. Passive Voice with Modals</h4>\r\n    <p>Incorporating modal verbs into passive constructions allows for expressing necessity, possibility, or obligation passively.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"The report must be submitted by Friday.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>3. Passive Infinitive</h4>\r\n    <p>Using the passive infinitive form enables us to discuss actions that are necessary or planned to be performed by someone else.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"The document is to be signed by all parties.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>4. Passive with Reporting Verbs</h4>\r\n    <p>When it comes to reporting speech or thoughts, passive structures offer a way to focus on the information or belief rather than the speaker.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"It is said that the museum houses the rarest jewels.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>5. Past Participles as Adjectives</h4>\r\n    <p>Often, past participles from passive constructions are utilized as adjectives to describe the subject’s state resulting from an action.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"The stolen jewels were never recovered.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>6. Using the Passive to Avoid Mentioning the Doer</h4>\r\n    <p>One of the classical uses of the passive voice is to omit the doer of the action, often because the doer is unknown, or it's unnecessary to specify them for the context.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"The decision was made to close the school due to bad weather.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <h4>7. Passive Causatives</h4>\r\n    <p>Passive causative structures allow us to express an action that is caused to happen to the subject by another agent. This is particularly useful in formal contexts, such as academic or technical writing.</p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><em>Example:</em> \"The artwork was had painted by a renowned artist.\"</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n\r\n    <p>Mastering these advanced passive constructions not only demonstrates a high level of fluency in English but also enriches your ability to communicate complex ideas effectively, making your speech or writing more versatile and engaging.</p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 6,
                            Order = 4,
                            Text = "Advanced Passive Constructions"
                        },
