                            GrammarTopicId = 109,
                            Description = "",
                            Explanation = "<div>\r\n    <p>\r\n    At the C2 level, students of English are expected to have a comprehensive understanding and application of advanced relative clauses. Relative clauses, which provide extra information about a noun, can significantly add depth to writing and speaking. Advanced usage includes a variety of structures and nuanced applications that go beyond the basic understanding of defining and non-defining relative clauses.\r\n    </p>\r\n\r\n    <h4>Types of Advanced Relative Clauses</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n    There are several advanced relative clause structures that learners should be familiar with:\r\n    </p>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>\r\n        <strong>Reduced Relative Clauses:</strong> These are relative clauses where the relative pronoun and auxiliary verbs are omitted when possible. For example, \"The book sitting on the table is mine\" instead of \"The book that is sitting on the table is mine\".\r\n        </li>\r\n        <li>\r\n        <strong>Relative Clauses with Prepositions:</strong> This involves placing prepositions at the beginning of the relative clause, especially in formal English. For example, \"The manager to whom you spoke is on vacation.\"\r\n        </li>\r\n        <li>\r\n        <strong>Relative Clauses with 'Whose', 'Where', and 'When':</strong> These clauses allow for more descriptive sentences. 'Whose' indicates possession, 'Where' is used for places, and 'When' for times. An example is, \"We visited the town, where my grandmother was born.\"\r\n        </li>\r\n        <li>\r\n        <strong>Infinitive Relative Clauses:</strong> These clauses use an infinitive form creating a more concise clause. For instance, \"I have something to tell you\" instead of \"I have something that I want to tell you.\"\r\n        </li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Nuances in Usage</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n    The choice between using a defining or a non-defining relative clause is crucial in advanced English. Defining relative clauses, which do not use commas, provide essential information about the noun. In contrast, non-defining relative clauses, which are set off with commas, add non-essential, extra information.\r\n    </p>\r\n    <p>\r\n    Another area of complexity is the pronoun selection in relative clauses. The use of 'that' versus 'which' in defining relative clauses, and the preference for 'which' in non-defining clauses, are pivotal in fine-tuning writing and speech. Additionally, choosing the appropriate relative pronoun depending on the antecedent (person, thing, place, time) can add clarity and precision.\r\n    </p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Practical Applications</h4>\r\n    <p>\r\n    Mastery of advanced relative clauses enhances expressive capability in English. Whether in academic writing, professional communication, or everyday conversation, these structures add subtlety and variety. They allow the speaker or writer to convey complex ideas succinctly and to embed detailed descriptions within a sentence.\r\n    </p>\r\n    <p>\r\n    Practicing these clauses can involve rewriting sentences to include relative clauses, identifying and correcting errors in their use, and composing sentences that use each type of advanced relative clause. Additionally, reading high-level texts and noting the use of these clauses can provide context and examples for learners.\r\n    </p>\r\n</div>",
                            LanguageLevelId = 6,
                            Order = 14,
                            Text = "Advanced Relative Clauses"
